==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*kūz'', from Indo-European ''*gʷōus''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[ku|kū]], Old Saxon [[ko|kō]] (Dutch [[koe]]), Old High German [[kuo]] (German [[Kuh]]), Old Norse [[kýr]] (Swedish [[ko]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Avestan ''gāu-'', Greek [[βους]], Latin [[bos]], Armenian [[կով]], Russian [[говядо]], Latvian [[guovs|gùovs]], Old Irish [[bó]], Tocharian A ''ko''.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ku:/

===Noun===
'''cū''' ''f''
#[[cow]]
#:''An cu wearþ gebroht to ðam temple'': a cow was brought to the temple.

